  "prompt": "How can sedimentary rocks contain fossils?",
  "response": "Sedimentary rocks can contain fossils through several processes:\n\n1. Burial and preservation\n- Organisms die and are quickly covered by sediment\n- Sediment protects remains from decay and scavenging\n- Layers of sediment accumulate and compress over time\n\n2. Mineralization processes\n- Mineral-rich water fills pores in organic remains\n- Minerals gradually replace original organic material\n- This creates a detailed fossil replica of the original organism\n\n3. Favorable conditions for fossil formation\n- Environments like ocean floors, river deltas, and lake bottoms\n- Areas with rapid sediment deposition\n- Low-oxygen environments that slow decomposition\n\n4. Types of fossil preservation\n- Permineralization (minerals fill cellular spaces)\n- Carbonization (thin carbon film remains)\n- Molds and casts (impressions of original organism)\n- Trace fossils (preserved tracks, burrows)\n\n5. Sedimentary rock formation\n- Sediments accumulate in layers\n- Pressure and compaction transform sediments into rock\n- Fossils become embedded and preserved within rock layers\n\nThese processes explain why sedimentary rocks are the primary source of fossil evidence for prehistoric life.",
